{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox person |name=Arie van Os |image=<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Arie van Os.jpeg]] --> |alt= |caption= |birth_name= |birth_date= 1937 |birth_place=[[Amsterdam]], [[North Holland]], [[Netherlands]] | death_date = | death_place = |occupation=[[Businessperson|Businessman]] }}
'''Arie van Os''' (born 1937 in [[Amsterdam]]) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Businessperson|businessman]] and [[Director of football|financial director]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ftm.nl/exclusive/hans-kroon-van-der-moolen-richard-den-drijver/ |title=Hans Kroon en Richard den Drijver duiken weer op |publisher=Follow The Money|date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref>
==Career== Arie van Os made his fortune as partner of the company [[Van der Moolen]]. In the eighties he was the director and chairman of the [[Amsterdam Stock Exchange]], together with his then flamboyant partner [[Hans Kroon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vorige.nrc.nl/international/article2324624.ece |title=Van der Moolen asks for creditor protection |publisher=NRC.nl|date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref>
In 1989 he became the financial director of [[AFC Ajax]] where his reputation grew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2844/Archief/archief/article/detail/581802/2001/06/01/Genadeloos-en-nors-maar-eerlijk.dhtml |title=Genadeloos en nors, maar eerlijk |publisher=Volkskrant.nl|date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref> He then spent three days in jail due to a tight policy on alleged tax malpractice on behalf of the club with the transfers of [[Michael Laudrup]] and [[Shota Arveladze]].
His position at the club was then succeeded by Ajax banker [[Hein Blocks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mt.nl/1/815/home/arie-van-os-kruidenier-van-ajax.html |title=Arie van Os, kruidenier van Ajax |publisher=MT.nl |date= |accessdate=2013-11-21}}</ref>
