{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} [[File:MYAdisNoAD.jpg|thumb|1980 billboard hijacking by [[John Fekner]]]] {{Anti-consumerism|Theories}}
'''Billboard hacking''' or '''billboard hijacking''' is the practice of altering a billboard without the consent of the owner. It may involve physically pasting new media over the existing image,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psfk.com/2012/07/british-billboards-hijacked-street-artists.html|title=Street Artists Hijack Billboards in UK [Pics]|last=Chen|first=Yi|date=19 July 2012|work=PSFK|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref> or hacking into the system used to control electronic [[billboard]] displays. The aim is to replace the programmed video with a different video or image. The replaced media may be displayed for various reasons, including [[culture jamming]], shock value, promotion, activism,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theurbancountry.com/2011/03/billboard-hijacking-to-promote-urban.html|title=Billboard Hijacking To Promote Urban Bicycling|last=Schwartz|first=James D.|date=7 March 2011|work=The Urban Country|type=Blog|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref> political propaganda,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news/city-billboards-hijacked-by-al|title=City billboards hijacked by AL|date=6 August 2013|work=The Daily Star|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref> or simply to amuse viewers.
== Self-promotion == A Russian daredevil group called [[Ontheroofs]] hacked into a billboard atop a skyscraper in Hong Kong, causing it to display the name of their organization, a video of a previous climb up the then unfinished [[Shanghai Tower]], and the words "What's Up Hong Kong".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/17/world/asia/on-the-roofs-climber/index.html|title=On the Roofs climbers scale new heights|last=McKirdy|first=Euan|date=18 October 2014|work=CNN|access-date=22 July 2017}}</ref>
Two college students in [[Belgrade]], Serbia hacked into a billboard and then contacted the owner describing the vulnerability. The hack allowed them to play ''[[Space Invaders]]'' and then display "Hacked4Fun". The students were thanked by the owner for pointing out the vulnerability and each given an [[iPad Mini]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/hackers-play-space-invaders-digital-billboard-owner-ipads/story?id=18736785|title=Hackers Play Space Invaders on Digital Billboard, Owner Gives Them iPads|last=Jovanovic|first=Dragana|date=15 March 2013|work=ABC News|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2013/03/hackers-play-space-invaders-on-belgrade-billboard-get-rewarded-with-ipads/|title=Hackers play Space Invaders on Belgrade billboard, get rewarded with iPads|last=Farivar|first=Cyrus|date=14 March 2013|work=Ars Technica|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>
In [[Republic Square, Belgrade|Republic Square]], Belgrade, Serbia, hackers caused a billboard to display an advertisement for [[The Pirate Bay]] which read "First they ignore you, then they laugh at you, then they fight you, then you win."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/pirate-bay-ad-shown-on-hacked-billboard/#!|title=Pirate Bay 'ad' shown on hacked billboard|last=Healey|first=Nic|date=12 March 2013|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=CNET|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>
== Activism == [[File:Billboard liberation front santa cruz.jpg|thumb|A billboard hijacked by the [[Billboard Liberation Front]]]] A group named "Brandalism" has been hacking European billboards since 2012. Around November 2015, just prior to the Paris climate talks ([[COP21]]), street artists joined with this group and gained control of around 600 billboards around Paris making display the message "We'll keep on bribing politicians and emitting greenhouse gases" and a Volkswagen promotion reading "We're sorry that we got caught."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citylab.com/design/2015/11/cop21-paris-climate-billboard-artist-volkswagen-brandalism/417897/|title=Activist-Artists Hack 600 Paris Billboards With Climate Messages for COP21|last=Metcalfe|first=John|date=30 November 2015|work=CityLab|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>
== Legal response == Depending on the circumstances, billboard hacking may be illegal. The [[FBI]] opened an investigation following the display of the obscene [[Goatse]] image on a billboard in [[Buckhead, Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/read/someone-hacked-a-billboard-in-atlanta-to-display-goatse|title=Someone Hacked a Billboard in Atlanta to Display Goatse|last=Koebler|first=Jason|date=15 May 2016|work=Motherboard|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grahamcluley.com/2015/05/hackers-obscene-electronic-billboard/|title=Hackers plant obscene image on electronic billboard in Atlanta|last=Cluley|first=Graham|work=Graham Cluley|publisher=Cluley Associates|date=21 May 2015|access-date=5 May 2016}}</ref> In another instance, one man was sentenced to 18 months in prison for displaying pornography on a Moscow billboard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/5785446/a-man-is-going-to-prison-for-hacking-a-billboard-to-play-porn-nsfw|title=A Man Is Going to Prison for Hacking a Billboard to Play Porn (NSFW)|last=Chan|first=Casey|date=24 March 2016|publisher=Gawker Media|work=Gizmodo|access-date=6 May 2016}}</ref>
== Methods == [[File:Its a bore.jpg|thumb|An example of hijacking using [[détournement]]]] Control over the display of electronic billboards may be achieved by hacking. One possible way of doing this is by knowing the default password provided by the manufacturer as the customer may neglect to choose a new one.
With non-electronic billboards, the image may simply be pasted over with a new image, or, the original image modified using the technique of [[détournement]].
