'''James Randall Corrigan''' (10 July 1865 – 19 March 1935) was a New Zealand [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal]] Party [[Member of Parliament]], farmer and businessman.

==Biography==
{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=right}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{NZ election link year|1922}}
 |end        = 1925
 |term       = 21st
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Patea}}
 |party      = New Zealand Liberal Party
}}
{{NZ parlbox footer}}
Born at [[Woodend, New Zealand|Woodend]], North Canterbury, Corrigan was a very successful farmer in the North Island, and breeder of sheep, cattle and trotting horses. He died in Hawera aged 69 years.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19350320.2.156?end_date=30-03-1935&phrase=0&query=corrigan&start_date=19-03-1935&type=ARTICLE |title=  Obituary |publisher=  ''New Zealand Herald''  |date= 20 March 1935 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19350321.2.171?end_date=1935-03-30&phrase=0&query=corrigan&start_date=1935-03-19&type=ARTICLE |title=  Obituary |publisher=  ''Auckland Star''  |date= 21 March 1935 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/PATM19350320.2.22?end_date=1935-03-30&phrase=0&query=corrigan&start_date=1935-03-19&type=ARTICLE |title=  Obituary |publisher=  ''Patea Mail''  |date= 20 March 1935 }}</ref>

James Corrigan represented the [[Patea (New Zealand electorate)|Patea]] electorate in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]] between 1922 and 1925.<ref name="Wilson">{{cite book |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand parliamentary record, 1840–1984 |edition= 4th |origyear= 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher= V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |isbn= |oclc= 154283103 |page=190}}</ref>

A daughter, Dorothy Corrigan, married the [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Nelson (New Zealand electorate)|Nelson]], [[Harry Atmore]], in 1936.<ref>''Harry Atmore: Independent in Politics'' by Simon Courtney (Undated, BA Hons Research Paper-University of Canterbury, Christchurch), page 4</ref>

